   {:e #blake3 "cd8608526ccbe600c4b8d3627385d3d7f21b93f467a365047450d0fce4550136" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "SESSION 032 DOG-FOODING — Improvement ideas: (1) Incremental F(S) via MaterializedViews — already designed and CE-1 shipped. CE-2..4 will complete wiring. (2) Store loading cache exists but invalidated by RFL-2 writes — W_alpha (CE-8) fixes by moving operational telemetry out of shared store. (3) Divergence footer compression — show '154 divergences (52 Aleatory, 8 Logical, 94 Temporal)' instead of listing each. One line, actionable. (4) Test lifecycle not just function — stale session bug, alert fatigue, session ident collision all share root cause: tested individual functions in isolation but not end-to-end lifecycle under realistic conditions (fast repeated calls, same-second timing, zero-delta transactions). E2E scripts explicitly test these now.; Session entity: :recon/trace-2f752afb71eb9356; SESSION 032 REFLECTION — MaterializedViews as keystone abstraction. The discovery that materialized views are the correct abstraction — not caching, not daemons — unifies everything: performance (O(1) reads), correctness (isomorphism with batch computation), the convergence proof (F(S) as Lyapunov function), and gradient routing (project_delta from accumulators). One idea, four consequences. That's the hallmark of a correct abstraction. The same pattern already exists in the Store (LIVE index is a materialized view). Extending it to F(S) is applying the system's own abstraction to its own coherence metric.; SESSION 032 DOG-FOODING — Positive: R(t) task routing genuinely useful, consistently selected COTX-1 (impact=0.28) as top priority which was correct. The observe-harvest cycle captures real discoveries (stale binary bug, session ident collision, alert fatigue bug). Task acceptance criteria are precise and actionable thanks to TAP-SPLIT. Session lifecycle is now self-healing via COTX-1 atomic rotation.; USER FEEDBACK SESSION 032 — User pushed repeatedly to 'go deeper, ruminate harder, be bolder' when I was producing tasks too quickly without grounding in spec. The pattern: user asks for review, I produce tasks, user says 'dig deeper,' I find a real gap, user says 'dig deeper,' I find a deeper gap. Three iterations: (1) daemon tasks -> (2) materialized views replacing daemon for perf -> (3) convergence engine unifying with existing spec formalizations. Each iteration was a 10x improvement in architectural clarity. Key user quotes: 'is this the best first principles approach possible?' and 'the adrs, specs, and guide markdown files should all be absorbed into the braid store and then deprecated.' User values: spec-groundedness, algebraic thinking, store-as-source-of-truth, cleanroom engineering.; SESSION 032 REFLECTION — The spec is smarter than any individual session. Every 'insight' from this session (materialized views, coherence gradient, self-steering, Lyapunov convergence) was already formalized in the spec: INV-BILATERAL-001 L1, INV-GUIDANCE-010 steepest descent, INV-COHERENCE-004 geodesic pursuit, INV-COHERENCE-013 entropy second law, ADR-COHERENCE-003 F(S) decomposition. The right move is almost always 'read the spec more carefully' rather than 'invent something new.' The spec is the distilled intelligence of the entire project history across 7 transcripts and 30+ sessions.; Session entity: :recon/trace-d100814b4d429013; SESSION 032 REFLECTION — Basin B pull is real. Edited spec markdown files directly (twice) instead of transacting through the store. Pretrained instinct is 'edit the file' not 'transact through the store.' The guidance system is designed to catch exactly this drift. Also: jumped to cache implementations (StatusSnapshot, file caches, inotify) before doing root cause analysis. Treated symptoms (redundant computation, cache misses) instead of diagnosing the structural divergence (process lifecycle mismatch, FD-012 vs INV-INTERFACE-008). Should have done algebraic root cause analysis FIRST before writing any code. The spec-first principle isn't just about writing specs — it's about understanding the problem algebraically before reaching for implementation.; SESSION 032 DOG-FOODING — Pain points: (1) braid status takes ~30s at 37K datoms — single biggest friction, makes every task execution slower, agents skip coherence checks. Convergence Engine Phase 0 fixes this. (2) CARGO_TARGET_DIR mismatch — build goes to /tmp/cargo-target/ but E2E scripts expect target/release/braid. Silent stale binary causes ghost failures. Must cp after every build. Procedural obligation DDIS should eliminate. (3) Harvest urgency residual false positives — alert fatigue bug (legacy fallback on zero-delta metabolic data) was present since Session 030, survived 3 sessions. Fixed by total_delta_count condition. (4) Divergence footer is noise — 'braid divergence — 154 active: Aleatory, Aleatory, ...' fills 3-4 terminal lines with repeated type names. Should compress to one line with counts.; SESSION 032 REFLECTION — Key lesson: do algebraic root cause analysis before implementation. The session's thrashing sequence was instructive: (1) tried StatusSnapshot compute-once (helped but didn't solve root cause), (2) tried file-level fitness/coherence caching (invalidated by RFL-2 writes), (3) tried read-only command exemption (violates FD-012), (4) tried inotify filesystem watching (OS-specific, not algebraically grounded). Each attempt was a Band-Aid on the wrong abstraction level. The correct answer (materialized views as Store fields) came only after deep spec research revealed the existing formalizations. The pattern: when thrashing on implementation, STOP and read the spec. The answer is usually already there.; Session entity: :recon/trace-91107e69d8fcc0c5; Session entity: :recon/trace-28e5a5ad0d7146a0" :op :assert}
